{"title_page": "Andrew Jack (dialect coach)", "text_new": "{{short description|British voice coach}}\n{{More citations|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| name = Andrew Jack\n| image = \n| caption = \n| pseudonym = \n| birth_name = Andrew Hutchinson\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1944|1|28|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[London]], [[England]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|2020|3|31|1944|1|28|df=y}}\n| death_place = [[Surrey]], [[England]]<ref name=\"death\"/>\n| occupation = [[Dialect coach]]\n| nationality = British\n| ethnicity = \n| citizenship = United Kingdom\n| education = \n| alma_mater = \n| period = 1982&ndash;2020\n| genre = \n| subject = \n| movement = \n| notableworks = \n| spouse = {{plainlist|\n* {{marriage|Felicity Hutchinson|1974|1987}}\n* {{marriage|Paula Jack|2000|2018}}\n* {{marriage|Gabrielle Rogers|2019|2020}}\n}}\n| partner = \n| children = 2\n| relatives = \n| influences = \n| influenced = \n| awards = \n| signature = \n| website = {{URL|andrewjack.com}}\n| portaldisp = \n}}\n'''Andrew Jack''' (born '''Andrew Hutchinson'''; 28 January 1944 \u2013 31 March 2020) was a British [[dialect coach]] and actor from [[London]] who had worked on over 80 motion pictures since 1982.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://movies.nytimes.com/person/408903/Andrew-Jack?scp=1&sq=andrew%20jack&st=cse |newspaper=The New York Times | title=Andrew Jack |url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|date=31 March 2020 |title=Actor Andrew Jack Dies of Coronavirus at 76 in Britain |newspaper=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2020/03/31/world/asia/ap-as-obit-andrew-jack.html |url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0413087/ \"Andrew Jack (I) (1944\u20132020)\" IMDB]</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nHis father Stephen Jack was an actor, and his mother Julia (n\u00e9e Hutchinson) was a horticulturist.{{Citation needed|date=November 2017}}\n\n==Career==\nHe had worked with over 200 actors<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.andrewjack.com/artistes-actors-actresses.htm |title=Archived copy of Official Webpage of Andrew Jack |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110703060353/http://www.andrewjack.com/artistes-actors-actresses.htm |archivedate=3 July 2011 }}</ref> including [[Robert Downey Jr.]] (in [[Richard Attenborough]]'s ''[[Chaplin (film)|Chaplin]]'', [[Michael Hoffman (American director)|Michael Hoffman]]'s ''[[Restoration (1995 film)|Restoration]]'' and [[Guy Ritchie]]'s ''[[Sherlock Holmes (2009 film)|Sherlock Holmes]]''), [[Pierce Brosnan]] (in ''[[GoldenEye]]'', ''[[Tomorrow Never Dies]]'' and ''[[Die Another Day]]''), [[Cate Blanchett]], and [[Viggo Mortensen]]. As supervising dialect coach for ''[[The Lord of the Rings (film series)|The Lord of the Rings]]'', he created the [[Middle-earth]] accents and taught them, along with [[Elvish]] and [[Black Speech]], to the cast of the trilogy.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Moore|first=Miranda|title=How Elijah Wood learned Elvish|journal=[[The Linguist]]|date=Feb\u2013Mar 2002}}</ref> He designed and taught the accents for the Greeks and [[Trojan language|Trojans]] in [[Wolfgang Petersen]]'s ''[[Troy (film)|Troy]]''. He taught [[Evan Davis]] to speak with a Nottinghamshire twang.<ref>{{cite news|last=Davis|first=Evan|title=Can Evan do a Robin Hood Accent?|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/today/hi/today/newsid_8680000/8680097.stm|accessdate=8 July 2011|publisher=BBC News|date=14 May 2010}}</ref> He was known for helping non-British actors to be more intelligible to the audience.<ref>{{cite news|last=Graydon|first=Nicola|title=The Lion Roars|newspaper=The Times|date=31 May 2004}}</ref>\n\nJack can also be seen in the [[Star Wars|''Star Wars'' film series]] portraying [[Resistance (Star Wars)|Resistance]] Major (later promoted to General) [[Caluan Ematt]] in ''[[Star Wars: The Force Awakens]]'' and ''[[Star Wars: The Last Jedi]]''. He also voiced the character of Moloch in ''[[Solo: A Star Wars Story]]''.{{Citation needed|date=March 2020}} The final film he was working on at the time of his death was ''[[The Batman (film)|The Batman]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Andrew Jack, 'Star Wars' actor, dies from Covid-19 |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/01/entertainment/andrew-jack-star-wars-coronavirus-dies-gbr-intl-scli/index.html |publisher=CNN|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life and death==\nJack's widow Gabrielle Rogers is also a voice, accent and dialect coach who first started working in the film, television and theatre industries as an actor in the 1980s.  Rogers and Jack were married until his death from [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] on 31 March 2020.<ref name=\"death\">{{cite news |title=Star Wars actor dies after contracting COVID-19 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-sussex-52111530 |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=BBC News |date=31 March 2020}}</ref> His wife Rogers wrote on [[Twitter]]:<ref>{{cite web |title=Rest in Peace Andrew Jack, Major Caluan Ematt |url=https://www.fanthatracks.com/news/conventions-events/rest-in-peace-andrew-jack-major-caluan-ematt/ |publisher=Fantha Tracks |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|We lost a man today. Andrew Jack was diagnosed with coronavirus two days ago. He was in no pain, and he slipped away peacefully knowing that his family were all 'with' him.}}\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n|2001|| ''[[Kate & Leopold]]'' || [[John A. Roebling|Roebling]] ||\n|-\n|2015|| ''[[Star Wars: The Force Awakens]]'' || rowspan=2|Caluan Ematt ||\n|-\n|2017|| ''[[Star Wars: The Last Jedi]]'' ||\n|-\n|2018|| ''[[Solo: A Star Wars Story]]'' || Moloch || Voice\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Imdb name|0413087|name=Andrew Jack}}\n\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jack, Andrew}}\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:British voice coaches]]\n[[Category:Film people from London]]\n[[Category:British actors]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British voice coach}}\n{{More citations|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| name = Andrew Jack\n| image = \n| caption = \n| pseudonym = \n| birth_name = Andrew Hutchinson\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1944|1|28|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[London]], [[England]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|2020|3|31|1944|1|28|df=y}}\n| death_place = [[Surrey]], [[England]]<ref name=\"death\"/>\n| occupation = [[Dialect coach]]\n| nationality = British\n| ethnicity = \n| citizenship = United Kingdom\n| education = \n| alma_mater = \n| period = 1982&ndash;2020\n| genre = \n| subject = \n| movement = \n| notableworks = \n| spouse = {{plainlist|\n* {{marriage|Felicity Hutchinson|1974|1987}}\n* {{marriage|Paula Jack|2000|2018}}\n* {{marriage|Gabrielle Rogers|2019|2020}}\n}}\n| partner = \n| children = 2\n| relatives = \n| influences = \n| influenced = \n| awards = \n| signature = \n| website = {{URL|andrewjack.com}}\n| portaldisp = \n}}\n'''Andrew Jack''' (born '''Andrew Hutchinson'''; 28 January 1944 \u2013 31 March 2020) was a British [[dialect coach]] and actor from [[London]] who had worked on over 80 motion pictures since 1982.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://movies.nytimes.com/person/408903/Andrew-Jack?scp=1&sq=andrew%20jack&st=cse |newspaper=The New York Times | title=Andrew Jack |url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|date=31 March 2020 |title=Actor Andrew Jack Dies of Coronavirus at 76 in Britain |newspaper=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2020/03/31/world/asia/ap-as-obit-andrew-jack.html |url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0413087/ \"Andrew Jack (I) (1944\u20132020)\" IMDB]</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nHis father Stephen Jack was an actor, and his mother Julia (n\u00e9e Hutchinson) was a horticulturist.{{Citation needed|date=November 2017}}\n\n==Career==\nHe had worked with over 200 actors<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.andrewjack.com/artistes-actors-actresses.htm |title=Archived copy of Official Webpage of Andrew Jack |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110703060353/http://www.andrewjack.com/artistes-actors-actresses.htm |archivedate=3 July 2011 }}</ref> including [[Robert Downey Jr.]] (in [[Richard Attenborough]]'s ''[[Chaplin (film)|Chaplin]]'', [[Michael Hoffman (American director)|Michael Hoffman]]'s ''[[Restoration (1995 film)|Restoration]]'' and [[Guy Ritchie]]'s ''[[Sherlock Holmes (2009 film)|Sherlock Holmes]]''), [[Pierce Brosnan]] (in ''[[GoldenEye]]'', ''[[Tomorrow Never Dies]]'' and ''[[Die Another Day]]''), [[Cate Blanchett]], and [[Viggo Mortensen]]. As supervising dialect coach for ''[[The Lord of the Rings (film series)|The Lord of the Rings]]'', he created the [[Middle-earth]] accents and taught them, along with [[Elvish]] and [[Black Speech]], to the cast of the trilogy.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Moore|first=Miranda|title=How Elijah Wood learned Elvish|journal=[[The Linguist]]|date=Feb\u2013Mar 2002}}</ref> He designed and taught the accents for the Greeks and [[Trojan language|Trojans]] in [[Wolfgang Petersen]]'s ''[[Troy (film)|Troy]]''. He taught [[Evan Davis]] to speak with a Nottinghamshire twang.<ref>{{cite news|last=Davis|first=Evan|title=Can Evan do a Robin Hood Accent?|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/today/hi/today/newsid_8680000/8680097.stm|accessdate=8 July 2011|publisher=BBC News|date=14 May 2010}}</ref> He was known for helping non-British actors to be more intelligible to the audience.<ref>{{cite news|last=Graydon|first=Nicola|title=The Lion Roars|newspaper=The Times|date=31 May 2004}}</ref>\n\nJack can also be seen in the [[Star Wars|''Star Wars'' film series]] portraying [[Resistance (Star Wars)|Resistance]] Major (later promoted to General) [[Caluan Ematt]] in ''[[Star Wars: The Force Awakens]]'' and ''[[Star Wars: The Last Jedi]]''. He also voiced the character of Moloch in ''[[Solo: A Star Wars Story]]''.{{Citation needed|date=March 2020}} The final film he was working on at the time of his death was ''[[The Batman (film)|The Batman]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Andrew Jack, 'Star Wars' actor, dies from Covid-19 |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/01/entertainment/andrew-jack-star-wars-coronavirus-dies-gbr-intl-scli/index.html |publisher=CNN|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life and death==\nJack's widow Gabrielle Rogers is also a voice, accent and dialect coach who first started working in the film, television and theatre industries as an actor in the 1980s.  Rogers and Jack were married until his death from [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] on 31 March 2020.<ref name=\"death\">{{cite news |title=Star Wars actor dies after contracting COVID-19 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-sussex-52111530 |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=BBC News |date=31 March 2020}}</ref> His wife Rogers wrote on [[Twitter]], \"We lost a man today. Andrew Jack was diagnosed with coronavirus two days ago. He was in no pain, and he slipped away peacefully knowing that his family were all 'with' him\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Rest in Peace Andrew Jack, Major Caluan Ematt |url=https://www.fanthatracks.com/news/conventions-events/rest-in-peace-andrew-jack-major-caluan-ematt/ |publisher=Fantha Tracks |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n|2001|| ''[[Kate & Leopold]]'' || [[John A. Roebling|Roebling]] ||\n|-\n|2015|| ''[[Star Wars: The Force Awakens]]'' || rowspan=2|Caluan Ematt ||\n|-\n|2017|| ''[[Star Wars: The Last Jedi]]'' ||\n|-\n|2018|| ''[[Solo: A Star Wars Story]]'' || Moloch || Voice\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Imdb name|0413087|name=Andrew Jack}}\n\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jack, Andrew}}\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:British voice coaches]]\n[[Category:Film people from London]]\n[[Category:British actors]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "Pigsonthewing", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePersonal life and death:fmt", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andrew_Jack_(dialect_coach)"}
{"title_page": "Biblical poetry", "text_new": "{{Tone|date=December 2009}}\nThe ancient [[Hebrews]] identified [[poetry|poetical]] portions in their [[sacred texts]], as shown by their entitling as \"[[song]]s\" or as \"[[chant]]s\" passages such as [[Book of Exodus|Exodus]] 15:1-19 and [[Book of Numbers|Numbers]] 21:17-20; a song or chant ({{transl|hbo|shir}}) is, according to the primary meaning of the term, [[poetry]]. The question as to whether the poetical passages of the Old Testament show signs of regular rhythm or meter remains unsolved.<ref>\n{{cite web\n | url= http://jewishencyclopedia.com/articles/10738-meter-in-the-bible\n | title= METER IN THE BIBLE | publisher= JewishEncyclopedia.com\n | accessdate= December 7, 2011 | author= Joseph Jacobs, W. H. Cobb\n}}\n</ref>\n\n== Characteristics of Ancient Hebrew poetry ==\n\n=== Unusual forms ===\nThe employment of unusual forms of language cannot be considered as a sign of ancient Hebrew poetry. In the sentences of [[Noah]]<ref>Such as [[Book of Genesis|Genesis]] 9:25-27.</ref> the form {{transl|hbo|lamo}} occurs. But this form, which represents partly {{transl|hbo|lahem}} and partly {{transl|hbo|lo}}, has many counterparts in Hebrew grammar, as, for example, {{transl|hbo|kemo}} instead of {{transl|hbo|ke-}};<ref>Exodus 15:5, 15:8.</ref> or {{transl|hbo|-emo}} = \"them\";<ref>15:9, 15:15.</ref> or {{transl|hbo|-emo}} = \"their\";<ref>[[Psalm 2]]:3.</ref> or {{transl|hbo|clemo}} = \"to them\"<ref>2:5.</ref>&mdash;forms found in passages for which no claim to poetical expressions is made. Then there are found {{transl|hbo|\u1e25ayeto}} = \"beast\",<ref>Genesis 1:24.</ref> {{transl|hbo|osri}} = \"tying\",<ref>49:11.</ref> and {{transl|hbo|yeshu'atah}} = \"salvation\"<ref>Psalm 3:3.</ref>&mdash;three forms that probably retain remnants of the old endings of the [[nominative]], [[genitive]], and [[Accusative case|accusative]]: {{transl|hbo|u(n),}} {{transl|hbo|i(n),}} {{transl|hbo|a(n).}}\n\nAgain, in [[Lamech (descendant of Cain)|Lamech]]'s words, \"[[Adah (biblical figure)|Adah]] and [[Zillah (biblical figure)|Zillah]], hear my voice; ye wives of Lamech, harken unto my speech\",<ref>Genesis 4:23.</ref> the two words {{transl|hbo|he'ezin}} and {{transl|hbo|imrah}} attract attention, because they occur for the first time in this passage, although there had been an earlier opportunity of using them: in Genesis 3:8 and 3:10, {{transl|hbo|He'ezin}} = \"to harken\" could have been used just as well as its synonym {{transl|hbo|shama'}} = \"to hear\".<ref>It occurs also in Exodus 15:26; Numbers 23:18 (a sentence of [[Balaam]]); [[Deuteronomy]] 1:45, 32:1; [[Book of Judges|Judges]] 5:3; [[Book of Isaiah|Isaiah]] 1:2, 1:10, 8:9, 28:23, 32:9, 42:23, 51:4, 44:3; [[Book of Jeremiah]] 13:15; [[Book of Hosea|Hosea]] 5:1; [[Book of Joel|Joel]] 1:2; [[Book of Nehemiah|Nehemiah]] 9:30 (in a prayer); and in [[Books of Chronicles|2 Chronicles]] 24:19 (probably an imitation of Isaiah 44:3).</ref>\n\nFurthermore, {{transl|hbo|imrah}} = \"speech\" might have been used instead of the essentially identical {{transl|hbo|dabar}} in Genesis 9:1 and following, but its earliest use is, as stated above, in Genesis 4:23.<ref>It is found also in Deuteronomy 32:2, 33:9; [[Books of Samuel|2 Samuel]] 22:31; Isaiah 5:24, 28:23, 39:4, 32:9; Psalm 12:7, etc.; [[Book of Proverbs|Proverbs]] 30:5; and [[Book of Lamentations|Lamentations]] 2:17.</ref> In place of {{transl|hbo|adam}} = \"man\"<ref>Genesis 1:26 and following.</ref> {{transl|hbo|enosh}} is employed.<ref>In Deuteronomy 32:26; Isaiah 8:1, 13:7, 13:12; 24:6, 33:8; 51:7, 51:12; 56:2; Jeremiah 20:10; Psalm 8:5, 9:20, 10:18, 55:14, 56:2, 66:12, 73:5, 90:3, 103:15, 104:15, 154:3; [[Book of Job|Job]] 4:17, 5:17, 7:1, 7:17, 9:2, 10:4; 13:9, 14:19, 15:14, 25:4, 25:6, 28:4, 28:13, 32:8; 33:12, 33:26, 36:25; 2 Chronicles 14:10.</ref> (compare the Aramaic {{transl|tmr|enash}}<ref>In [[Book of Daniel|Daniel]] 2:10; [[Book of Ezra|Ezra]] 4:11, 6:11.</ref>).\n\nA [[systematic review]] of similar unusual forms of Hebrew grammar and Hebrew words occurring in certain portions of the Old Testament.<ref>See [[E. K\u00f6nig]], {{lang|de|Stilistik}}, etc., p. 277-283.</ref> Such forms have been called {{lang|la|dialectus poetica}} since the publication of [[Robert Lowth]]'s {{lang|la|Pr\u00e6lectiones de Sacra Poesi Hebr\u00e6orum}} iii. (1753); but this designation is ambiguous and can be accepted only in agreement with the rule {{lang|la|a parte potiori fit denominatio}} for some of these unusual forms and words are found elsewhere than in the \"songs\" of the Old Testament.\n\nThese unusual forms and expressions do not occur in all songs, and there are several Psalms that have none of these peculiarities.\n\n=== Parallelism ===\n{{main|Parallelism (rhetoric)}}\nNot even the {{lang|la|parallelismus membrorum}} is an absolutely certain indication of ancient Hebrew poetry. This \"parallelism\" occurs in the portions of the Hebrew Bible that are at the same time marked frequently by the so-called {{lang|la|dialectus poetica}}; it consists in a remarkable correspondence in the ideas expressed in two successive units (hemistiches, verses, strophes, or larger units); for example, the above-cited words of Lamech, \"Adah and Zillah, hear my voice; ye wives of Lamech, harken unto my speech\",<ref>Genesis 4:23</ref> in which are found {{transl|hbo|he'ezin}} and {{transl|hbo|imrah,}} show a remarkable repetition of the same thought.\n\nBut this ideal corythmy is not always present in the songs of the [[Old Testament]] or in the Psalter, as the following passages will show:\n* \"The Lord is my strength and song, and he is become my salvation\" ({{bibleverse|Exodus|15:2|9}}).\n* \"[[Saul the King| Saul]] and [[David and Jonathan| Jonathan]], the beloved and the lovely, in life and in death they were not divided\".<ref>H. P. Smith, in \"International Commentary,\" on 2 Samuel 1:23.</ref>\n* \"Ye daughters of Israel, weep over Saul, who clothed you in scarlet, and fine linen\".<ref>2 Samuel 1:24/</ref>\n* \"And he shall be like a tree planted by the rivers of water, that bringeth forth his fruit in his season\";<ref>Psalm 1:3; compare 2:12.</ref>\n* \"I laid me down and slept; I awaked; for the Lord sustained me. I will not be afraid of ten thousands of people, that have set themselves against me round about\".<ref>Psalm 3:6-7 [A. V. 5-6]; see also 4:7 and following, 9:4 and following.</ref>\n\n[[Julius Ley]]<ref>\n{{cite book\n | last1 = Ley\n | first1 = Julius\n | chapter = Vom Versbau\n | title = Leitfaden der Metrik der hebr\u00e4ischen Poesie: nebst dem ersten Buche der Psalmen : nach rhythmischer Vers- und Strophenabteilung mit metrischer Analyse\n | trans-title = Outlines of the meter of Hebrew poetry: along with the first Book of Psalms: divided by rhythmic verse and stanza with metrical analysis\n | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=IfwoAAAAYAAJ\n | series = ATLA monograph preservation program\n | language = German\n | location = Halle an der Saale\n | publisher = Verlag der Buchhandlung des Waisenhauses\n | publication-date = 1887\n | page = 10\n | access-date = 14 Mar 2019\n | quote = So sehr auch der Parallelismus die ausgepr\u00e4gte Form der hebr\u00e4ischen Vesbildung ist, so halten sich die Dichter nicht der Art durch denselben gebunden, dass sie es nicht, wo der Gedanke es erfordert, denselben durchbrechen sollten.\n}}\n</ref> says therefore correctly that\n\n:\"the poets did not consider themselves bound by parallelism to such an extent as not to set it aside when the thought required it.\"\n\nThough this restriction must be made to James Robertson's view, it remains the case that:<ref>\"The Poetry of the Psalms\", 1898, p. 160.</ref> \"The distinguishing feature of the Hebrew poetry ... is the rhythmical balancing of parts, or parallelism of thought.\"\n\nVarious [[rhetoric]]al forms appear in the parallelisms of Biblical poetry.  These include:\n\n* [[Synonym]]ous parallelism; in this form, the second unit ([[hemistich]] or half line of verse, verse, strophe, or larger unit) says much the same thing as the first one, with variations.  An example appears in [[Book of Amos|Amos]] [[Amos 5:24|5:24]]:\n\n:''But let judgment run down as waters,''\n::''and righteousness as a mighty stream.''\n\nAnother example of synonymous parallelism comes in [[Book of Isaiah|Isaiah]] [[Isaiah 2:4|2:4]] or [[Book of Micah|Micah]] 4:3:\n\n:\"They will beat their swords into plowshares''\n::''and their spears into pruning hooks.''\n\n* [[Antithesis]] is also found; here, the second unit directly contrasts with the first, often making the same point from the opposite perspective.  From [[Book of Proverbs|Proverbs]] 10:1:\n\n:''A wise son maketh a glad father,''\n::''but a foolish son'' is ''the heaviness of his mother.''\n\n* Emblematic parallelism occurs where one unit renders figuratively the literal meaning of another.\n* Synthetic parallelism occurs where the units balance, clause for clause, with one unit building upon or adding to the first.  From Psalm 14:2:\n\n:''The {{LORD}} looked down from heaven upon the children of men,''\n::''to see if there were any that did understand'' and ''seek God.''\n\n* [[Climax (figure of speech)| Climactic]] parallelism occurs where the second unit partially balances the first, but also adds a summative thought or completes the series.  From Psalm 29:1:\n\n:''Give unto the {{LORD}}, O ye mighty,''\n::''give unto the {{LORD}} glory and strength.''\n\n* External parallelism occurs when the syntactic units balance one another across multiple verses.  Here, some of the permitted sorts of parallelisms are added not only within a single line of verse, but also between lines.  From Isaiah 1:27-28:\n\n:''Zion shall be redeemed with judgment,''\n::''and her converts with righteousness.''\n:''And the destruction of the transgressors and the sinners'' shall be ''together,''\n::''and they that forsake the {{LORD}} shall be consumed.''\n\nExternal parallelism can also \"accumulate\" in a chiastic or \"ring\" structure that may include many verses.  For example, Psalm 1 utilizes synonymous, synthetic, and emblematic parallelism before \"turning\" antithetically back to emblematic, synthetic, and then synonymous parallels.\n\n=== Quantitative Rhythm ===\nThe poetry of the ancient Hebrews is not distinguished from the other parts of the Old Testament by rhythm based on quantity, though in view of Greek and Roman poetry it was natural to seek such a rhythm in the songs and Psalms of the Old Testament. [[William Jones (philologist)|William Jones]], for example,<ref>{{lang|la|Poeseos Asiatic\u00e6 Commentarii}}, chapter 2, London, 1774</ref> attempted to prove that there was a definite sequence of long and short syllables in the ancient Hebrew poems; but he could support this thesis only by changing the punctuation in many ways, and by allowing great license to the Hebrew poets. However, on reading the portions of the Old Testament marked by the so-called {{lang|la|dialectus poetica}} or by parallelism (e.g., Genesis 4:23 and following) no such sequence of long and short syllables can be discovered; and [[Sievers]]<ref>{{lang|de|Metrische Untersuchungen,}} 1901, \u00a7 53.</ref> says: \"Hebrew prosody is not based on quantity as classical prosody is.\"\n\n=== Accentual rhythm ===\nMany scholars hold that the Hebrew poet considered only the syllables receiving the main accent, and did not count the intervening ones. Examples contrary to this are not found in passages where forms of the so-called {{lang|la|dialectus poetica}} are used, as Ley holds;<ref>In his {{lang|de|Grundz\u00fcge des Rhythmus, des Vers- und Strophenbaues in der Hebr\u00e4ischen Poesie}}, p. 99, p. 116.</ref> and [[Israel Davidson]] has proved<ref>In his {{lang|de|Stilistik}}, p. 333, for example.</ref> that the choice of {{transl|hbo|lamo}} instead of {{transl|hbo|lahem}} favors in only a few passages the opinion that the poet intended to cause an accented syllable to be followed by an unaccented one.\n\nThe rhythm of Hebrew poetry may be similar to that of the German {{lang|de|[[Nibelungenlied]]}} &mdash; a view that is strongly supported by the nature of the songs sung by the populace of [[Palestine (region)|Palestine]] in the early 20th century. These songs have been described by [[L. Schneller]]<ref>In his {{lang|de|Kennst Du das Land?}} (section {{lang|de|Musik}}).</ref> in the following words:\n\n:\"The rhythms are manifold; there may be eight accents in one line, and three syllables are often inserted between two accents, the symmetry and variation being determined by emotion and sentiment.\"\n\nAlso in Palestine, [[Gustaf Hermann Dalman]] observed:\n\nn:\"Lines with two, three, four, and five accented syllables may be distinguished, between which one to three, and even four, unaccented syllables may be inserted, the poet being bound by no definite number in his poem. Occasionally two accented syllables are joined\" ({{lang|de|Pal\u00e4stinischer Diwan}}, 1901, p. 23).\n\nSuch free rhythms are, in Davidson's opinion, found also in the poetry of the Old Testament. Under the stress of their thoughts and feelings the poets of Israel sought to achieve merely the material, not the formal symmetry of corresponding lines. This may be observed, for example, in the following lines of Psalm 2: \"Serve the {{LORD}} with fear\" ({{transl|hbo|'Ibdu et-Yhwh be-yir'ah}}, 2:11), \"rejoice with trembling\" ({{transl|hbo|we-gilu bi-re'adah}}). This is shown more in detail by K\u00f6nig;<ref>l.c. p. 334.</ref> and [[Carl Heinrich Cornill]] has confirmed this view<ref>{{lang|de|Die Metrischen St\u00fccke des Buches Jeremia}}, 1901, p. 8.</ref> by saying:\n\n:\"Equal length of the several stichoi was not the basic formal law of Jeremiah's metric construction.\"\n\nSievers is inclined to restrict Hebrew rhythm by various rules, as he attacks<ref>l.c. \u00a7\u00a7 52, 88.</ref> [[Karl Budde]]'s view, that\n\n:\"a foot which is lacking in one-half of a verse may find a substitute in the more ample thought of this shorter line\".<ref>{{lang|de|Handkommentar zu Hiob}}, p. 47.</ref>\n\nFurthermore, the verse of the Old Testament poetry is naturally [[Iamb (foot)|iambic]] or [[Anapaest|anapestic]], as the words are accented on one of the final syllables.\n\n=== The Dirges ===\nA special kind of rhythm may be observed in the [[dirge]]s, called by the Hebrews {{transl|hbo|kinot}}. A whole book of these elegies is contained in the [[Hebrew Bible]], the first of them beginning thus: \"How does the city sit solitary&mdash;that was full of people&mdash;how is she become as a widow&mdash;she that was great among the nations&mdash;and princess among the provinces&mdash;how is she become tributary!\" (Lamentations 1:1).\n\nThe rhythm of such lines lies in the fact that a longer line is always followed by a shorter one. As in the [[elegiac couplet]] of Greco-Roman poetry, this change was intended to symbolize the idea that a strenuous advance in life is followed by fatigue or reaction. This rhythm, which may be designated \"elegiac measure,\" occurs also in Amos 5:2, expressly designated as a \u1e33inah. The sad import of his prophecies induced Jeremiah also to employ the rhythm of the dirges several times in his utterances (Jeremiah 9:20, 13:18 and following). He refers here expressly to the {{transl|hbo|me\u1e33onenot}} (the mourning women) who in the East still chant the death-song to the trembling tone of the pipe (48:36 and following). {{transl|hbo|\u1e32inot}} are found also in [[Book of Ezekiel|Ezekiel]] 19:1, 26:17, 27:2, 32:2 and following, 32:16, 32:19 and following.\n\nThis elegiac measure, being naturally a well-known one, was used also elsewhere, as, for example, in Psalm 19:8-10. The rhythm of the \u1e33inah has been analyzed especially by Budde (in Stade's {{lang|de|Zeitschrift}}, 1883, p. 299). Similar funeral songs of the modern [[Arab]]s are quoted by Wetzstein (in {{lang|de|Zeitschrift f\u00fcr Ethnologie}}, v. 298), as, e.g.: \"O, if he only could be ransomed! truly, I would pay the ransom!\" (see K\u00f6nig, l.c. p. 315).\n\n=== Anadiplosis ===\nA special kind of rhythm was produced by the frequent employment of the so-called anadiplosis, a mode of speech in which the phrase at the end of one sentence is repeated at the beginning of the next, as, for instance, in the passages \"they came not to the help of the Lord [i.e., to protect God's people], to the help of the Lord against the mighty\" (Judges 5:23; compare {{transl|hbo|\u1e93id\u1e33ot}} [5:11a] and {{transl|hbo|nil\u1e25amu}} [5:19a-20a, b]), and \"From whence shall my help come? My help cometh from the Lord\" (Psalm 121:1b-2a, R. V.).\n\nMany similar passages occur in fifteen of the Psalms, 120-134, which also contain an unusual number of epanalepsis, or catch-words, for which Israel Davidson proposed the name {{lang|de|Leitt\u00f6ne.}} Thus there is the repetition of {{transl|hbo|shakan}} in Psalm 120:5, 6; of {{transl|hbo|shalom}} in verses 6 and 7 of the same psalm; and the catch-word {{transl|hbo|yishmor}} in Psalm 121:7, 8 (all the cases are enumerated in K\u00f6nig, l.c. p.&nbsp;302).\n\nAs the employment of such repetitions is somewhat suggestive of the mounting of stairs, the superscription {{transl|hbo|shir ha-ma'alot,}} found at the beginning of these fifteen psalms, may have a double meaning: it may indicate not only the purpose of these songs, to be sung on the pilgrimages to the festivals at [[Jerusalem]], but also the peculiar construction of the songs, by which the reciter is led from one step of the inner life to the next. Such graduated rhythm may be observed elsewhere; for the peasants in modern [[Syria]] accompany their national dance by a song the verses of which are connected like the links of a chain, each verse beginning with the final words of the preceding one (Wetzstein, l.c. v. 292).\n\n=== Acrostics ===\nAlphabetical [[acrostic]]s are used as an external embellishment of a few poems. The letters of the alphabet, generally in their ordinary sequence, stand at the beginning of smaller or larger sections of Psalms 9-10 (probably), 25, 34, 37, 111, 112, 119, 145; Proverbs 31:10-31; Lamentations 1-4; and also of Sirach 51:13-29, as the newly discovered Hebrew text of this book has shown (see, on Psalms 25 and 34 especially, Hirsch in \"Am. Jour. Semit. Lang.\" 1902, p. 167-173).\n\nAlphabetical and other acrostics occur frequently in Neo-Hebraic poetry.<ref>Winter and W\u00fcnsche, {{lang|de|Die J\u00fcdische Literatur seit Abschluss des Kanons,}} 1894-1896, iii. 10.</ref> The existence of acrostics in Babylonian literature has been definitely proved;<ref>[[H. Zimmern]], in {{lang|de|Zeitschrift f\u00fcr Keilschriftforschung,}} 1895, p. 15.</ref> and alphabetical poems are found also among the Samaritans, Syrians, and Arabs. Cicero says ({{lang|la|De Divinatione,}} II.54) that the verse of the sibyl was in acrostics; and the so-called {{lang|la|[[Oracula Sibyllina]]}} contain an acrostic.<ref>In book 8, lines 217-250.</ref>\n\nA secondary phenomenon, which distinguishes a part of the poems of the Old Testament from the other parts, is the so-called {{lang|la|[[accentuatio poetica]]}}; it has been much slighted (Sievers, l.c. \u00a7 248, p.&nbsp;375). Although not all the poetical portions of the Old Testament are marked by a special accentuation, the Book of Job in 3:3-42:6 and the books of Psalms and Proverbs throughout have received unusual accents. This point will be further discussed later on.\n\n== Division of the poetical portions of the Hebrew Bible ==\n\n=== Poems that deal with events ===\nFirst may be mentioned poems that deal principally with events, being epic-lyric in character: the triumphal song of Israel delivered from Egypt, or the ''[[song of the sea]]'';<ref>Exodus 15:1-18.</ref> the mocking song on the burning of [[Heshbon]];<ref>Numbers 21:27-30.</ref> the so-called ''[[song of Moses]]'';<ref>Deuteronomy 32:1-43.</ref> the [[song of Deborah]];<ref>Judges 5.</ref> the derisive song of victory of the Israelite women;<ref>\"Saul hath slain,\" etc.; 1 Samuel 18:7</ref> [[Hannah (Bible)|Hannah]]'s song of praise;<ref>2:1-10.</ref> [[David]]'s song of praise on being saved from his enemies;<ref>2 Samuel 22.</ref> [[Hezekiah]]'s song of praise on his recovery;<ref>Isaiah 38:9-20.</ref> [[Jonah]]'s song of praise;<ref>[[Book of Jonah|Jonah]] 2:3-10.</ref> and many of the Psalms, e.g., those on the creation of the world,<ref>8, 104).</ref> and on the election of Israel.<ref>99, 100, 105.</ref> A subdivision is formed by poems that deal more with description and praise: the so-called Well song;<ref>Numbers 21:17 and following.</ref> the song of praise on the uniqueness of the god of Israel;<ref>Psalms 95, 97.</ref> and those on his eternity;<ref>90.</ref> his omnipresence and omniscience;<ref>139.</ref> and his omnipotence.<ref>115.</ref>\n\n=== Didactic poems ===\nPoems appealing more to reason, being essentially [[didactic]] in character. These include [[fable]]s, like that of [[Jotham]] (Judges 9:7-15, although in prose); [[parable]]s, like those of [[Nathan (Prophet)|Nathan]] and others (2 Samuel 12:1-4, 14:4-9; [[Books of Kings|1 Kings]] 20:39 and following, all three in prose), or in the form of a song (Isaiah 5:1-6); [[riddle]]s (Judges 14:14 and following; Proverbs 30:11 and following); maxims, as, for instance, in 1 Samuel 15:22, 24:14, and the greater part of Proverbs; the monologues and dialogues in Job 3:3 and following; compare also the reflections in monologue in [[Ecclesiastes]]. A number of the Psalms also are didactic in character. A series of them impresses the fact that God's law teaches one to abhor sin (Psalms 5, 58), and inculcates a true love for the Temple and the feasts of Yahweh (Psalms 15, 81, 92). Another series of Psalms shows that God is just, although it may at times not seem this way to a short-sighted observer of the world and of history (\"theodicies\": Psalms 49, 73; compare Psalms 16, 56, 60).\n\n=== Lyrics ===\nPoems that portray feelings based on individual experience. Many of these lyrics express joy, as, e.g., Lamech's so-called ''[[Song of the sword]]'';<ref>Beginning at Genesis 4:23.</ref> David's \"last words\";<ref>2 Samuel 23:1-7.</ref> the words of praise of liberated Israel;<ref>Isaiah 12:1-6.</ref> songs of praise like Psalms 18, 24, 126, etc. Other lyrics express mourning. First among these are the dirges proper for the dead, as the [[\u1e33inah]] on the death of Saul and Jonathan;<ref>2 Samuel 1:19-27.</ref> that on [[Abner]]'s death;<ref>3:33 and following.</ref> and all psalms of mourning, as, e.g., the expressions of sorrow of sufferers,<ref>Psalms 16, 22, 27, 39.</ref> and the expressions of penitence of sinners.<ref>6, 32, 38, 51, 106, 130, 143.</ref>\n\n=== Poems that urge action ===\nFinally, a large group of poems of the Old Testament that urge action and are exhortatory. These may be divided into two sections:\n\n# The poet wishes something for himself, as in the so-called \"signal words\" (Numbers 10:35 and following, \"Arise, {{LORD}}\" etc.); at the beginning of the Well song (21:17 and following, {{transl|hbo|ali be'er}}); in the daring request, \"Sun, stand thou still\" ([[Book of Joshua|Joshua]] 10:12); in [[Habakkuk]]'s prayer ({{transl|hbo|tefillah}}; [[Book of Habakkuk|Habakkuk]] 3:1-19); or in psalms of request for help in time of war (44, 60, etc.) or for liberation from prison (122, 137, etc.).\n# The poet pronounces blessings upon others, endeavoring to move God to grant these wishes. To this group belong the blessing of Noah (Genesis 9:25-27), of [[Isaac]] (27:28-29 and 39-40), and of [[Jacob]] (49:3-27); [[Jethro (Bible)|Jethro]]'s congratulation of Israel (Exodus 18:10); the blessing of [[Aaron]] (Numbers 6:24-26) and of [[Balaam]] (23:7-10, 18-24, 24:5-9, 24:17-24); Moses' farewell (Deuteronomy 33:1 and following); the psalms that begin with {{transl|hbo|Ashre}} = \"Blessed is,\" etc., or contain this phrase, as Psalms 1, 41, 84:5 and following, 84:13, 112, 119, 128.\n\nIt was natural that in the drama, which is intended to portray a whole series of external and internal events, several of the foregoing kinds of poems should be combined. This combination occurs in [[Song of Songs|Canticles]], which, in Davidson's opinion, is most correctly characterized as a kind of drama.\n\nThe peculiar sublimity of the poems of the Old Testament is due partly to the high development of monotheism which finds expression therein and partly to the beauty of the moral ideals which they exalt. This subject has been discussed  by [[J. D. Michaelis]] in the preface to his Arabic grammar, second edition, p29, and by [[Emil Kautzsch]] in {{lang|de|Die Poesie und die Poetischen B\u00fccher des A. T.}} (1902)\nalthough this all may be true he Hebrew poetry follows a totally different rhyming scheme and as it has been translated into English we cannot comprehend this.\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Poetry}}\n*[[Poetry]]\n*[[Hebrew Bible]]\n*[[Yemenite Jewish poetry]]\n*[[List of national poetries]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n*{{JewishEncyclopedia}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{Cite book | edition = Second | publisher = Basic Books | isbn = 0-465-02256-1 | last = Alter | first = Robert | title = The Art of Biblical Poetry | date = 2011-09-06 | authorlink = Robert Alter }}\n*{{Cite book | publisher = W. W. Norton & Company | isbn = 0-393-33704-9 | last = Alter | first = Robert | title = The Book of Psalms: A Translation with Commentary | date = 2009-10-19 | authorlink = Robert Alter }}\n* Tod Linafelt, \"Private Poetry and Public Rhetoric: Hearing and Overhearing David's Lament for Saul and Jonathan in 2 Samuel 1,\" in the ''Journal of Religion'' 88:4 (2008), 497-526.\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.houseofdavid.ca/anc_heb.htm Biblical Hebrew Poetry - Reconstructing the Original Oral, Aural and Visual Experience]\n* [http://jewishencyclopedia.com/view.jsp?artid=388&letter=P#0 Jewish Encyclopedia - Poetry - Biblical]\n*{{CathEncy|wstitle=Hebrew Poetry of the Old Testament}}\n\n{{Poetry of different cultures and languages}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Biblical Poetry}}\n[[Category:Hebrew Bible topics]]\n[[Category:Poetry by nation or language]]\n[[Category:Christian genres]]\n[[Category:Religious poetry]]\n", "text_old": "{{Tone|date=December 2009}}\nThe ancient [[Hebrews]] identified [[poetry|poetical]] portions in their [[sacred texts]], as shown by their entitling as \"[[song]]s\" or as \"[[chant]]s\" passages such as [[Book of Exodus|Exodus]] 15:1-19 and [[Book of Numbers|Numbers]] 21:17-20; a song or chant ({{transl|hbo|shir}}) is, according to the primary meaning of the term, [[poetry]]. The question as to whether the poetical passages of the Old Testament show signs of regular rhythm or meter remains unsolved.<ref>\n{{cite web\n | url= http://jewishencyclopedia.com/articles/10738-meter-in-the-bible\n | title= METER IN THE BIBLE | publisher= JewishEncyclopedia.com\n | accessdate= December 7, 2011 | author= Joseph Jacobs, W. H. Cobb\n}}\n</ref>\n\n== Characteristics of Ancient Hebrew poetry ==\n\n=== Unusual forms ===\nThe employment of unusual forms of language cannot be considered as a sign of ancient Hebrew poetry. In the sentences of [[Noah]]<ref>Such as [[Book of Genesis|Genesis]] 9:25-27.</ref> the form {{transl|hbo|lamo}} occurs. But this form, which represents partly {{transl|hbo|lahem}} and partly {{transl|hbo|lo}}, has many counterparts in Hebrew grammar, as, for example, {{transl|hbo|kemo}} instead of {{transl|hbo|ke-}};<ref>Exodus 15:5, 15:8.</ref> or {{transl|hbo|-emo}} = \"them\";<ref>15:9, 15:15.</ref> or {{transl|hbo|-emo}} = \"their\";<ref>[[Psalm 2]]:3.</ref> or {{transl|hbo|clemo}} = \"to them\"<ref>2:5.</ref>&mdash;forms found in passages for which no claim to poetical expressions is made. Then there are found {{transl|hbo|\u1e25ayeto}} = \"beast\",<ref>Genesis 1:24.</ref> {{transl|hbo|osri}} = \"tying\",<ref>49:11.</ref> and {{transl|hbo|yeshu'atah}} = \"salvation\"<ref>Psalm 3:3.</ref>&mdash;three forms that probably retain remnants of the old endings of the [[nominative]], [[genitive]], and [[Accusative case|accusative]]: {{transl|hbo|u(n),}} {{transl|hbo|i(n),}} {{transl|hbo|a(n).}}\n\nAgain, in [[Lamech (descendant of Cain)|Lamech]]'s words, \"[[Adah (biblical figure)|Adah]] and [[Zillah (biblical figure)|Zillah]], hear my voice; ye wives of Lamech, harken unto my speech\",<ref>Genesis 4:23.</ref> the two words {{transl|hbo|he'ezin}} and {{transl|hbo|imrah}} attract attention, because they occur for the first time in this passage, although there had been an earlier opportunity of using them: in Genesis 3:8 and 3:10, {{transl|hbo|He'ezin}} = \"to harken\" could have been used just as well as its synonym {{transl|hbo|shama'}} = \"to hear\".<ref>It occurs also in Exodus 15:26; Numbers 23:18 (a sentence of [[Balaam]]); [[Deuteronomy]] 1:45, 32:1; [[Book of Judges|Judges]] 5:3; [[Book of Isaiah|Isaiah]] 1:2, 1:10, 8:9, 28:23, 32:9, 42:23, 51:4, 44:3; [[Book of Jeremiah]] 13:15; [[Book of Hosea|Hosea]] 5:1; [[Book of Joel|Joel]] 1:2; [[Book of Nehemiah|Nehemiah]] 9:30 (in a prayer); and in [[Books of Chronicles|2 Chronicles]] 24:19 (probably an imitation of Isaiah 44:3).</ref>\n\nFurthermore, {{transl|hbo|imrah}} = \"speech\" might have been used instead of the essentially identical {{transl|hbo|dabar}} in Genesis 9:1 and following, but its earliest use is, as stated above, in Genesis 4:23.<ref>It is found also in Deuteronomy 32:2, 33:9; [[Books of Samuel|2 Samuel]] 22:31; Isaiah 5:24, 28:23, 39:4, 32:9; Psalm 12:7, etc.; [[Book of Proverbs|Proverbs]] 30:5; and [[Book of Lamentations|Lamentations]] 2:17.</ref> In place of {{transl|hbo|adam}} = \"man\"<ref>Genesis 1:26 and following.</ref> {{transl|hbo|enosh}} is employed.<ref>In Deuteronomy 32:26; Isaiah 8:1, 13:7, 13:12; 24:6, 33:8; 51:7, 51:12; 56:2; Jeremiah 20:10; Psalm 8:5, 9:20, 10:18, 55:14, 56:2, 66:12, 73:5, 90:3, 103:15, 104:15, 154:3; [[Book of Job|Job]] 4:17, 5:17, 7:1, 7:17, 9:2, 10:4; 13:9, 14:19, 15:14, 25:4, 25:6, 28:4, 28:13, 32:8; 33:12, 33:26, 36:25; 2 Chronicles 14:10.</ref> (compare the Aramaic {{transl|tmr|enash}}<ref>In [[Book of Daniel|Daniel]] 2:10; [[Book of Ezra|Ezra]] 4:11, 6:11.</ref>).\n\nA [[systematic review]] of similar unusual forms of Hebrew grammar and Hebrew words occurring in certain portions of the Old Testament.<ref>See [[E. K\u00f6nig]], {{lang|de|Stilistik}}, etc., p. 277-283.</ref> Such forms have been called {{lang|la|dialectus poetica}} since the publication of [[Robert Lowth]]'s {{lang|la|Pr\u00e6lectiones de Sacra Poesi Hebr\u00e6orum}} iii. (1753); but this designation is ambiguous and can be accepted only in agreement with the rule {{lang|la|a parte potiori fit denominatio}} for some of these unusual forms and words are found elsewhere than in the \"songs\" of the Old Testament.\n\nThese unusual forms and expressions do not occur in all songs, and there are several Psalms that have none of these peculiarities.\n\n=== Parallelism ===\n{{main|Parallelism (rhetoric)}}\nNot even the {{lang|la|parallelismus membrorum}} is an absolutely certain indication of ancient Hebrew poetry. This \"parallelism\" occurs in the portions of the Old Testament that are at the same time marked frequently by the so-called {{lang|la|dialectus poetica}}; it consists in a remarkable correspondence in the ideas expressed in two successive units (hemistiches, verses, strophes, or larger units); for example, the above-cited words of Lamech, \"Adah and Zillah, hear my voice; ye wives of Lamech, harken unto my speech\",<ref>Genesis 4:23</ref> in which are found {{transl|hbo|he'ezin}} and {{transl|hbo|imrah,}} show a remarkable repetition of the same thought.\n\nBut this ideal corythmy is not always present in the songs of the [[Old Testament]] or in the Psalter, as the following passages will show:\n* \"The Lord is my strength and song, and he is become my salvation\" ({{bibleverse|Exodus|15:2|9}}).\n* \"[[Saul the King| Saul]] and [[David and Jonathan| Jonathan]], the beloved and the lovely, in life and in death they were not divided\".<ref>H. P. Smith, in \"International Commentary,\" on 2 Samuel 1:23.</ref>\n* \"Ye daughters of Israel, weep over Saul, who clothed you in scarlet, and fine linen\".<ref>2 Samuel 1:24/</ref>\n* \"And he shall be like a tree planted by the rivers of water, that bringeth forth his fruit in his season\";<ref>Psalm 1:3; compare 2:12.</ref>\n* \"I laid me down and slept; I awaked; for the Lord sustained me. I will not be afraid of ten thousands of people, that have set themselves against me round about\".<ref>Psalm 3:6-7 [A. V. 5-6]; see also 4:7 and following, 9:4 and following.</ref>\n\n[[Julius Ley]]<ref>\n{{cite book\n | last1 = Ley\n | first1 = Julius\n | chapter = Vom Versbau\n | title = Leitfaden der Metrik der hebr\u00e4ischen Poesie: nebst dem ersten Buche der Psalmen : nach rhythmischer Vers- und Strophenabteilung mit metrischer Analyse\n | trans-title = Outlines of the meter of Hebrew poetry: along with the first Book of Psalms: divided by rhythmic verse and stanza with metrical analysis\n | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=IfwoAAAAYAAJ\n | series = ATLA monograph preservation program\n | language = German\n | location = Halle an der Saale\n | publisher = Verlag der Buchhandlung des Waisenhauses\n | publication-date = 1887\n | page = 10\n | access-date = 14 Mar 2019\n | quote = So sehr auch der Parallelismus die ausgepr\u00e4gte Form der hebr\u00e4ischen Vesbildung ist, so halten sich die Dichter nicht der Art durch denselben gebunden, dass sie es nicht, wo der Gedanke es erfordert, denselben durchbrechen sollten.\n}}\n</ref> says therefore correctly that\n\n:\"the poets did not consider themselves bound by parallelism to such an extent as not to set it aside when the thought required it.\"\n\nThough this restriction must be made to James Robertson's view, it remains the case that:<ref>\"The Poetry of the Psalms\", 1898, p. 160.</ref> \"The distinguishing feature of the Hebrew poetry ... is the rhythmical balancing of parts, or parallelism of thought.\"\n\nVarious [[rhetoric]]al forms appear in the parallelisms of Biblical poetry.  These include:\n\n* [[Synonym]]ous parallelism; in this form, the second unit ([[hemistich]] or half line of verse, verse, strophe, or larger unit) says much the same thing as the first one, with variations.  An example appears in [[Book of Amos|Amos]] [[Amos 5:24|5:24]]:\n\n:''But let judgment run down as waters,''\n::''and righteousness as a mighty stream.''\n\nAnother example of synonymous parallelism comes in [[Book of Isaiah|Isaiah]] [[Isaiah 2:4|2:4]] or [[Book of Micah|Micah]] 4:3:\n\n:\"They will beat their swords into plowshares''\n::''and their spears into pruning hooks.''\n\n* [[Antithesis]] is also found; here, the second unit directly contrasts with the first, often making the same point from the opposite perspective.  From [[Book of Proverbs|Proverbs]] 10:1:\n\n:''A wise son maketh a glad father,''\n::''but a foolish son'' is ''the heaviness of his mother.''\n\n* Emblematic parallelism occurs where one unit renders figuratively the literal meaning of another.\n* Synthetic parallelism occurs where the units balance, clause for clause, with one unit building upon or adding to the first.  From Psalm 14:2:\n\n:''The {{LORD}} looked down from heaven upon the children of men,''\n::''to see if there were any that did understand'' and ''seek God.''\n\n* [[Climax (figure of speech)| Climactic]] parallelism occurs where the second unit partially balances the first, but also adds a summative thought or completes the series.  From Psalm 29:1:\n\n:''Give unto the {{LORD}}, O ye mighty,''\n::''give unto the {{LORD}} glory and strength.''\n\n* External parallelism occurs when the syntactic units balance one another across multiple verses.  Here, some of the permitted sorts of parallelisms are added not only within a single line of verse, but also between lines.  From Isaiah 1:27-28:\n\n:''Zion shall be redeemed with judgment,''\n::''and her converts with righteousness.''\n:''And the destruction of the transgressors and the sinners'' shall be ''together,''\n::''and they that forsake the {{LORD}} shall be consumed.''\n\nExternal parallelism can also \"accumulate\" in a chiastic or \"ring\" structure that may include many verses.  For example, Psalm 1 utilizes synonymous, synthetic, and emblematic parallelism before \"turning\" antithetically back to emblematic, synthetic, and then synonymous parallels.\n\n=== Quantitative Rhythm ===\nThe poetry of the ancient Hebrews is not distinguished from the other parts of the Old Testament by rhythm based on quantity, though in view of Greek and Roman poetry it was natural to seek such a rhythm in the songs and Psalms of the Old Testament. [[William Jones (philologist)|William Jones]], for example,<ref>{{lang|la|Poeseos Asiatic\u00e6 Commentarii}}, chapter 2, London, 1774</ref> attempted to prove that there was a definite sequence of long and short syllables in the ancient Hebrew poems; but he could support this thesis only by changing the punctuation in many ways, and by allowing great license to the Hebrew poets. However, on reading the portions of the Old Testament marked by the so-called {{lang|la|dialectus poetica}} or by parallelism (e.g., Genesis 4:23 and following) no such sequence of long and short syllables can be discovered; and [[Sievers]]<ref>{{lang|de|Metrische Untersuchungen,}} 1901, \u00a7 53.</ref> says: \"Hebrew prosody is not based on quantity as classical prosody is.\"\n\n=== Accentual rhythm ===\nMany scholars hold that the Hebrew poet considered only the syllables receiving the main accent, and did not count the intervening ones. Examples contrary to this are not found in passages where forms of the so-called {{lang|la|dialectus poetica}} are used, as Ley holds;<ref>In his {{lang|de|Grundz\u00fcge des Rhythmus, des Vers- und Strophenbaues in der Hebr\u00e4ischen Poesie}}, p. 99, p. 116.</ref> and [[Israel Davidson]] has proved<ref>In his {{lang|de|Stilistik}}, p. 333, for example.</ref> that the choice of {{transl|hbo|lamo}} instead of {{transl|hbo|lahem}} favors in only a few passages the opinion that the poet intended to cause an accented syllable to be followed by an unaccented one.\n\nThe rhythm of Hebrew poetry may be similar to that of the German {{lang|de|[[Nibelungenlied]]}} &mdash; a view that is strongly supported by the nature of the songs sung by the populace of [[Palestine (region)|Palestine]] in the early 20th century. These songs have been described by [[L. Schneller]]<ref>In his {{lang|de|Kennst Du das Land?}} (section {{lang|de|Musik}}).</ref> in the following words:\n\n:\"The rhythms are manifold; there may be eight accents in one line, and three syllables are often inserted between two accents, the symmetry and variation being determined by emotion and sentiment.\"\n\nAlso in Palestine, [[Gustaf Hermann Dalman]] observed:\n\nn:\"Lines with two, three, four, and five accented syllables may be distinguished, between which one to three, and even four, unaccented syllables may be inserted, the poet being bound by no definite number in his poem. Occasionally two accented syllables are joined\" ({{lang|de|Pal\u00e4stinischer Diwan}}, 1901, p. 23).\n\nSuch free rhythms are, in Davidson's opinion, found also in the poetry of the Old Testament. Under the stress of their thoughts and feelings the poets of Israel sought to achieve merely the material, not the formal symmetry of corresponding lines. This may be observed, for example, in the following lines of Psalm 2: \"Serve the {{LORD}} with fear\" ({{transl|hbo|'Ibdu et-Yhwh be-yir'ah}}, 2:11), \"rejoice with trembling\" ({{transl|hbo|we-gilu bi-re'adah}}). This is shown more in detail by K\u00f6nig;<ref>l.c. p. 334.</ref> and [[Carl Heinrich Cornill]] has confirmed this view<ref>{{lang|de|Die Metrischen St\u00fccke des Buches Jeremia}}, 1901, p. 8.</ref> by saying:\n\n:\"Equal length of the several stichoi was not the basic formal law of Jeremiah's metric construction.\"\n\nSievers is inclined to restrict Hebrew rhythm by various rules, as he attacks<ref>l.c. \u00a7\u00a7 52, 88.</ref> [[Karl Budde]]'s view, that\n\n:\"a foot which is lacking in one-half of a verse may find a substitute in the more ample thought of this shorter line\".<ref>{{lang|de|Handkommentar zu Hiob}}, p. 47.</ref>\n\nFurthermore, the verse of the Old Testament poetry is naturally [[Iamb (foot)|iambic]] or [[Anapaest|anapestic]], as the words are accented on one of the final syllables.\n\n=== The Dirges ===\nA special kind of rhythm may be observed in the [[dirge]]s, called by the Hebrews {{transl|hbo|kinot}}. A whole book of these elegies is contained in the [[Hebrew Bible]], the first of them beginning thus: \"How does the city sit solitary&mdash;that was full of people&mdash;how is she become as a widow&mdash;she that was great among the nations&mdash;and princess among the provinces&mdash;how is she become tributary!\" (Lamentations 1:1).\n\nThe rhythm of such lines lies in the fact that a longer line is always followed by a shorter one. As in the [[elegiac couplet]] of Greco-Roman poetry, this change was intended to symbolize the idea that a strenuous advance in life is followed by fatigue or reaction. This rhythm, which may be designated \"elegiac measure,\" occurs also in Amos 5:2, expressly designated as a \u1e33inah. The sad import of his prophecies induced Jeremiah also to employ the rhythm of the dirges several times in his utterances (Jeremiah 9:20, 13:18 and following). He refers here expressly to the {{transl|hbo|me\u1e33onenot}} (the mourning women) who in the East still chant the death-song to the trembling tone of the pipe (48:36 and following). {{transl|hbo|\u1e32inot}} are found also in [[Book of Ezekiel|Ezekiel]] 19:1, 26:17, 27:2, 32:2 and following, 32:16, 32:19 and following.\n\nThis elegiac measure, being naturally a well-known one, was used also elsewhere, as, for example, in Psalm 19:8-10. The rhythm of the \u1e33inah has been analyzed especially by Budde (in Stade's {{lang|de|Zeitschrift}}, 1883, p. 299). Similar funeral songs of the modern [[Arab]]s are quoted by Wetzstein (in {{lang|de|Zeitschrift f\u00fcr Ethnologie}}, v. 298), as, e.g.: \"O, if he only could be ransomed! truly, I would pay the ransom!\" (see K\u00f6nig, l.c. p. 315).\n\n=== Anadiplosis ===\nA special kind of rhythm was produced by the frequent employment of the so-called anadiplosis, a mode of speech in which the phrase at the end of one sentence is repeated at the beginning of the next, as, for instance, in the passages \"they came not to the help of the Lord [i.e., to protect God's people], to the help of the Lord against the mighty\" (Judges 5:23; compare {{transl|hbo|\u1e93id\u1e33ot}} [5:11a] and {{transl|hbo|nil\u1e25amu}} [5:19a-20a, b]), and \"From whence shall my help come? My help cometh from the Lord\" (Psalm 121:1b-2a, R. V.).\n\nMany similar passages occur in fifteen of the Psalms, 120-134, which also contain an unusual number of epanalepsis, or catch-words, for which Israel Davidson proposed the name {{lang|de|Leitt\u00f6ne.}} Thus there is the repetition of {{transl|hbo|shakan}} in Psalm 120:5, 6; of {{transl|hbo|shalom}} in verses 6 and 7 of the same psalm; and the catch-word {{transl|hbo|yishmor}} in Psalm 121:7, 8 (all the cases are enumerated in K\u00f6nig, l.c. p.&nbsp;302).\n\nAs the employment of such repetitions is somewhat suggestive of the mounting of stairs, the superscription {{transl|hbo|shir ha-ma'alot,}} found at the beginning of these fifteen psalms, may have a double meaning: it may indicate not only the purpose of these songs, to be sung on the pilgrimages to the festivals at [[Jerusalem]], but also the peculiar construction of the songs, by which the reciter is led from one step of the inner life to the next. Such graduated rhythm may be observed elsewhere; for the peasants in modern [[Syria]] accompany their national dance by a song the verses of which are connected like the links of a chain, each verse beginning with the final words of the preceding one (Wetzstein, l.c. v. 292).\n\n=== Acrostics ===\nAlphabetical [[acrostic]]s are used as an external embellishment of a few poems. The letters of the alphabet, generally in their ordinary sequence, stand at the beginning of smaller or larger sections of Psalms 9-10 (probably), 25, 34, 37, 111, 112, 119, 145; Proverbs 31:10-31; Lamentations 1-4; and also of Sirach 51:13-29, as the newly discovered Hebrew text of this book has shown (see, on Psalms 25 and 34 especially, Hirsch in \"Am. Jour. Semit. Lang.\" 1902, p. 167-173).\n\nAlphabetical and other acrostics occur frequently in Neo-Hebraic poetry.<ref>Winter and W\u00fcnsche, {{lang|de|Die J\u00fcdische Literatur seit Abschluss des Kanons,}} 1894-1896, iii. 10.</ref> The existence of acrostics in Babylonian literature has been definitely proved;<ref>[[H. Zimmern]], in {{lang|de|Zeitschrift f\u00fcr Keilschriftforschung,}} 1895, p. 15.</ref> and alphabetical poems are found also among the Samaritans, Syrians, and Arabs. Cicero says ({{lang|la|De Divinatione,}} II.54) that the verse of the sibyl was in acrostics; and the so-called {{lang|la|[[Oracula Sibyllina]]}} contain an acrostic.<ref>In book 8, lines 217-250.</ref>\n\nA secondary phenomenon, which distinguishes a part of the poems of the Old Testament from the other parts, is the so-called {{lang|la|[[accentuatio poetica]]}}; it has been much slighted (Sievers, l.c. \u00a7 248, p.&nbsp;375). Although not all the poetical portions of the Old Testament are marked by a special accentuation, the Book of Job in 3:3-42:6 and the books of Psalms and Proverbs throughout have received unusual accents. This point will be further discussed later on.\n\n== Division of the poetical portions of the Hebrew Bible ==\n\n=== Poems that deal with events ===\nFirst may be mentioned poems that deal principally with events, being epic-lyric in character: the triumphal song of Israel delivered from Egypt, or the ''[[song of the sea]]'';<ref>Exodus 15:1-18.</ref> the mocking song on the burning of [[Heshbon]];<ref>Numbers 21:27-30.</ref> the so-called ''[[song of Moses]]'';<ref>Deuteronomy 32:1-43.</ref> the [[song of Deborah]];<ref>Judges 5.</ref> the derisive song of victory of the Israelite women;<ref>\"Saul hath slain,\" etc.; 1 Samuel 18:7</ref> [[Hannah (Bible)|Hannah]]'s song of praise;<ref>2:1-10.</ref> [[David]]'s song of praise on being saved from his enemies;<ref>2 Samuel 22.</ref> [[Hezekiah]]'s song of praise on his recovery;<ref>Isaiah 38:9-20.</ref> [[Jonah]]'s song of praise;<ref>[[Book of Jonah|Jonah]] 2:3-10.</ref> and many of the Psalms, e.g., those on the creation of the world,<ref>8, 104).</ref> and on the election of Israel.<ref>99, 100, 105.</ref> A subdivision is formed by poems that deal more with description and praise: the so-called Well song;<ref>Numbers 21:17 and following.</ref> the song of praise on the uniqueness of the god of Israel;<ref>Psalms 95, 97.</ref> and those on his eternity;<ref>90.</ref> his omnipresence and omniscience;<ref>139.</ref> and his omnipotence.<ref>115.</ref>\n\n=== Didactic poems ===\nPoems appealing more to reason, being essentially [[didactic]] in character. These include [[fable]]s, like that of [[Jotham]] (Judges 9:7-15, although in prose); [[parable]]s, like those of [[Nathan (Prophet)|Nathan]] and others (2 Samuel 12:1-4, 14:4-9; [[Books of Kings|1 Kings]] 20:39 and following, all three in prose), or in the form of a song (Isaiah 5:1-6); [[riddle]]s (Judges 14:14 and following; Proverbs 30:11 and following); maxims, as, for instance, in 1 Samuel 15:22, 24:14, and the greater part of Proverbs; the monologues and dialogues in Job 3:3 and following; compare also the reflections in monologue in [[Ecclesiastes]]. A number of the Psalms also are didactic in character. A series of them impresses the fact that God's law teaches one to abhor sin (Psalms 5, 58), and inculcates a true love for the Temple and the feasts of Yahweh (Psalms 15, 81, 92). Another series of Psalms shows that God is just, although it may at times not seem this way to a short-sighted observer of the world and of history (\"theodicies\": Psalms 49, 73; compare Psalms 16, 56, 60).\n\n=== Lyrics ===\nPoems that portray feelings based on individual experience. Many of these lyrics express joy, as, e.g., Lamech's so-called ''[[Song of the sword]]'';<ref>Beginning at Genesis 4:23.</ref> David's \"last words\";<ref>2 Samuel 23:1-7.</ref> the words of praise of liberated Israel;<ref>Isaiah 12:1-6.</ref> songs of praise like Psalms 18, 24, 126, etc. Other lyrics express mourning. First among these are the dirges proper for the dead, as the [[\u1e33inah]] on the death of Saul and Jonathan;<ref>2 Samuel 1:19-27.</ref> that on [[Abner]]'s death;<ref>3:33 and following.</ref> and all psalms of mourning, as, e.g., the expressions of sorrow of sufferers,<ref>Psalms 16, 22, 27, 39.</ref> and the expressions of penitence of sinners.<ref>6, 32, 38, 51, 106, 130, 143.</ref>\n\n=== Poems that urge action ===\nFinally, a large group of poems of the Old Testament that urge action and are exhortatory. These may be divided into two sections:\n\n# The poet wishes something for himself, as in the so-called \"signal words\" (Numbers 10:35 and following, \"Arise, {{LORD}}\" etc.); at the beginning of the Well song (21:17 and following, {{transl|hbo|ali be'er}}); in the daring request, \"Sun, stand thou still\" ([[Book of Joshua|Joshua]] 10:12); in [[Habakkuk]]'s prayer ({{transl|hbo|tefillah}}; [[Book of Habakkuk|Habakkuk]] 3:1-19); or in psalms of request for help in time of war (44, 60, etc.) or for liberation from prison (122, 137, etc.).\n# The poet pronounces blessings upon others, endeavoring to move God to grant these wishes. To this group belong the blessing of Noah (Genesis 9:25-27), of [[Isaac]] (27:28-29 and 39-40), and of [[Jacob]] (49:3-27); [[Jethro (Bible)|Jethro]]'s congratulation of Israel (Exodus 18:10); the blessing of [[Aaron]] (Numbers 6:24-26) and of [[Balaam]] (23:7-10, 18-24, 24:5-9, 24:17-24); Moses' farewell (Deuteronomy 33:1 and following); the psalms that begin with {{transl|hbo|Ashre}} = \"Blessed is,\" etc., or contain this phrase, as Psalms 1, 41, 84:5 and following, 84:13, 112, 119, 128.\n\nIt was natural that in the drama, which is intended to portray a whole series of external and internal events, several of the foregoing kinds of poems should be combined. This combination occurs in [[Song of Songs|Canticles]], which, in Davidson's opinion, is most correctly characterized as a kind of drama.\n\nThe peculiar sublimity of the poems of the Old Testament is due partly to the high development of monotheism which finds expression therein and partly to the beauty of the moral ideals which they exalt. This subject has been discussed  by [[J. D. Michaelis]] in the preface to his Arabic grammar, second edition, p29, and by [[Emil Kautzsch]] in {{lang|de|Die Poesie und die Poetischen B\u00fccher des A. T.}} (1902)\nalthough this all may be true he Hebrew poetry follows a totally different rhyming scheme and as it has been translated into English we cannot comprehend this.\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Poetry}}\n*[[Poetry]]\n*[[Hebrew Bible]]\n*[[Yemenite Jewish poetry]]\n*[[List of national poetries]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n*{{JewishEncyclopedia}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{Cite book | edition = Second | publisher = Basic Books | isbn = 0-465-02256-1 | last = Alter | first = Robert | title = The Art of Biblical Poetry | date = 2011-09-06 | authorlink = Robert Alter }}\n*{{Cite book | publisher = W. W. Norton & Company | isbn = 0-393-33704-9 | last = Alter | first = Robert | title = The Book of Psalms: A Translation with Commentary | date = 2009-10-19 | authorlink = Robert Alter }}\n* Tod Linafelt, \"Private Poetry and Public Rhetoric: Hearing and Overhearing David's Lament for Saul and Jonathan in 2 Samuel 1,\" in the ''Journal of Religion'' 88:4 (2008), 497-526.\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.houseofdavid.ca/anc_heb.htm Biblical Hebrew Poetry - Reconstructing the Original Oral, Aural and Visual Experience]\n* [http://jewishencyclopedia.com/view.jsp?artid=388&letter=P#0 Jewish Encyclopedia - Poetry - Biblical]\n*{{CathEncy|wstitle=Hebrew Poetry of the Old Testament}}\n\n{{Poetry of different cultures and languages}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Biblical Poetry}}\n[[Category:Hebrew Bible topics]]\n[[Category:Poetry by nation or language]]\n[[Category:Christian genres]]\n[[Category:Religious poetry]]\n", "name_user": "Vasyaivanov", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eParallelism", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Biblical_poetry"}
